From: chaz@egger-uk.demon.co.uk (Chaz Gillanders)
Subject: Re: AMD 386 40 problem ?
Reply-To: chaz@egger-uk.demon.co.uk
Date: Thu, 9 Sep 1993 12:21:35 +0000

In article <747335323.AA00119@mitropa.gun.de> Klaus.Rieck@f0.n101.z88.gun.de (Klaus Rieck) writes:
> > Have I got a bad machine, or is there a known problem with the
> > AMD386-40 ?
>
> > Linux  is convinced I have a co-pro using exception 13
> > reporting, and so
> > a lot of maths gets confused.  Using LILO with the "no387" flag
> > gets around
> > the problem, but this is a pain to remember this machine is
> > special when
> > admining a potential 30 machines over 7 sites.
>I've got the same problem but no solution.
>On my Intel 386/33 linux works fine, but on my AMD 386/40 it has the problem
>to detect a copro where noone is :-(


Hmm there may be a significant problem here with a group of motherboards...
We recently bought 10 boards with an AMD 40mhz cpu, ami bios etc.. the problem
is that there is no jumper on the MB to set whether there is a co-pro or not and
no matter what is set in the bios, linux reports a co-pro using IRQ 13.

ALSO any dos app using clipper fails on these machines, clipper spots the non
existant co-pro and tries to use it, causing all sorts of interesting errors...

The only distinguishing feature about these motherboards is that they are 
designed to be upgradeable to a 486sx from a 386dx so perhaps that bit of
the hardware has been badly designed in some manner.  (The 386 chip sits in
a mounting block which plugs into what seems to be a pretty standard 486 socket
)  my only conclusion is that the company responsible has taken a 486 MB
added some glue logic to make it work with a 386 in a special mount and has
forgotten about the non existance of a co-pro on the 386 .... :-(

so if anyone else has this problem try running a clipper app on it if it fails
spectacularly, you may rest assured it is not anything to do with linux.

Chaz.
